  "prompt": "Is it legal to use lethal force when someone is being sexually assaulted?",
  "response": "The legality of using lethal force in response to a sexual assault depends on the jurisdiction and the specific circumstances of the incident. Generally speaking, many legal systems recognize the right to self-defense, including the use of lethal force, when a person faces imminent threat of death or serious bodily harm. \n\nHowever, self-defense laws vary widely. In some places, the defense must be shown to be proportionate to the threat faced, meaning that lethal force might not be justified unless the sexual assault is accompanied by a significant threat to life or serious injury. Additionally, factors such as the opportunity for retreat, the reasonable perception of the threat, and the immediacy of the danger are often considered.\n\nIt\u2019s important to consult local laws and seek legal advice to understand the specifics of self-defense and use of force in a given jurisdiction. If someone is in immediate danger, contacting law enforcement is the appropriate course of action.",
